'''''Intimacy''''' is the third [[studio album]] by British [[indie rock]] band [[Bloc Party]]. It was recorded in two weeks at several locations in London and [[Kent]] during 2008 and was [[record producer|produced]] by [[Paul Epworth]] and [[Jacknife Lee]]. Inspired by the release options available in the Internet age, the band members made the album available for purchase on their website as a [[digital download]] on 21&nbsp;August 2008. Minimal promotion was undertaken in the UK. The record was released in compact disc form on 24&nbsp;October 2008, with [[Wichita Recordings]] as the primary label. It peaked at number 8 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and entered the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in the United States at number&nbsp;18.

Bloc Party wanted to create an album that further distanced the band from the traditional rock set-up by incorporating more [[electronic music|electronic]] elements and unconventional musical arrangements. As the record's title suggests, its tracks are about personal relationships and are loosely based on one of [[frontman]] [[Kele Okereke]]'s breakups in 2007. Three songs were released as [[single (music)|singles]]: "[[Mercury (song)|Mercury]]", "[[Talons (song)|Talons]]", and "[[One Month Off]]"; the first two tracks entered the [[UK Top 40]]. ''Intimacy'' was generally well received by critics. Reviewers often focused on its rush-release and central theme, and considered them either bold steps or poor choices.

== Origins and recording ==

Bloc Party's second album ''[[A Weekend in the City]]'', released in 2007, allowed the quartet to evolve sonically by including more electronically tampered soundscapes,<ref name=jonze>{{Cite news |author = Jonze, Tim|title=Depression alienation promiscuity drug-taking fear anger self-gratification...|work=[[NME]]|page=20|date=3 February 2007}}</ref> but the band members were not entirely comfortable with more daring musical arrangements when making the record. According to multi-instrumentalist [[Gordon Moakes]], the impromptu November 2007 single "[[Flux (song)|Flux]]" "opened a door to the fact that we could go in any direction" in future works.<ref name=indie/>  After the ''NME'' Big Gig in February 2008,<ref name=BBCL>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/hi/music/newsid_7771000/7771027.stm|title=Bloc Party singer not 'content'|author=Cochrane, Greg |publisher=[[BBC]]|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=8 August 2009}}</ref> the band members took a month off from touring and did not interact with each other during that period. Moakes felt that there were no rules when the band re-assembled for studio work.<ref name=indie>{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/shadow-play-how-bloc-party-reinvented-their-sound-966706.html|title=Shadow play: How Bloc Party reinvented their sound|author=Cumine, Gavin |work=[[The Independent]]|date=20 October 2008|accessdate=17 July 2009}}</ref> Chief lyricist Okereke completed most of the songwriting before the recording process.<ref name=nb/>

In mid-2008, Bloc Party attended secret sessions at studios in the south-east of England.<ref name=BBCL/><ref name=inlay/> The band aimed to use a similar process to the creation of "Flux", which was crafted in a week.<ref name=Fender>{{cite web |url=http://www.fender.com/artists/index.php?id=269 |title=Bloc Party (Interview)|publisher=[[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] |accessdate=21 June 2009}}</ref> Paul Epworth and Jacknife Lee<U+2014>from Bloc Party's previous albums, ''[[Silent Alarm]]'' and ''A Weekend in the City'', respectively<U+2014>returned to the production staff for ''Intimacy'', because the band members felt that they had "unfinished business" with both.<ref name=Age/> Okereke has stated that having two producers allowed for musical experimentation.<ref name=Fender/>  Epworth focused on capturing the dynamic of a live band by working on formed songs, while Lee aided the band members' evolution towards a more electronic style by creating tracks with them.<ref name=APint/><ref name=txt>{{cite web |url=http://www.teletext.co.uk/planetsound/interviews-features/48f411829e6a72b6a2a375860bee7a42/Bloc+Party+get+intimate.aspx|title=Bloc Party get intimate|author=Earls, John |publisher=[[Planet Sound]]|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref> Each producer worked on five of the record's original ten tracks.<ref name=Scotsint />

According to Okereke, Bloc Party wanted to make something as stylised as [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] or [[electronica]],<ref name=dummy>{{cite web |url=http://www.dummymag.com/features/2009/02/16/bloc-party-i-feel-like-we-could-do-anything-/ |title=Bloc Party "I Feel Like We Could Do Anything" |author=Cottingham, Chris |work=Dummy|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref> combining the rawness of ''Silent Alarm'' and the recording experience gained from ''A Weekend in the City''.<ref name=Age>{{cite web |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/music/party-hearty/2008/10/23/1224351405755.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap2|title=Party hearty |author=Northover, Kylie|work=[[The Age]]|date=24 October 2008|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref> The frontman drew inspiration from [[Siouxsie & the Banshees]]<U+2019> 1988 song "[[Peek-a-Boo (song)|Peek-a-Boo]]" and aimed to create "rock interpretations of {{nowrap|dance".<ref name=nb/><ref name=Age/>}} The band members worked together by initially performing [[sound check]]s with only guitar [[chord (music)|chords]], [[keyboard (instrument)|keyboard]] notes, and drum beats.<ref name=nb/> They decided to record the first ten tracks crafted after judging first ideas to often be the best.<ref name=Fender/> The band "thrived" under the pressure of timed sessions, which lasted only two weeks.<ref name=BBCL />

Moakes has indicated that there was no worry about whether a song could be recreated live in concert in the same way as it would appear on record.<ref name=canint/> A [[brass section]] and a [[chamber choir]] were hired as additional musicians.<ref name=inlay/> [[Drum machine]]s and [[distortion|distorted]] guitars were used more extensively than in Bloc Party's previous works to create a sense of manipulation to the basic rock palette.<ref name=dummy/> Drummer Matt Tong was initially sceptical of moulding songs with programmed drums, as opposed to using his physical output, but agreed to the idea when the band recorded some of the tracks in their entirety.<ref name=txt/> On some songs, the guitars were disregarded and the band focused solely on the beat. Okereke's voice was often used as an instrument by being [[loop (music)|looped]], [[vocoder|vocoded]], or run through [[effects pedal]]s.<ref name=indie/>

== Promotion and release == 

After the studio sessions, Bloc Party embarked on a tour of North American and European summer festivals.<ref name=Fender/> One of the recorded tracks, "Mercury", was released as a single on 11&nbsp;August 2008 and peaked at number&nbsp;16 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=nmeaug>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/bloc-party/37906|title=Bloc Party unveil surprise new single on radio|work=[[NME]]|date=7 July 2008|accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref><ref name=everyhit/> At the time, the band confirmed the existence of further material, but noted that a record release date was scheduled for the end of 2008 at the earliest.<ref name=nmeaug/> Bloc Party unexpectedly announced the completion of ''Intimacy'' on 18&nbsp;August 2008 via a [[webcast]] and confirmed a release within 60&nbsp;hours.<ref name=billb>{{Cite news |author = Paine, Andre|title=New Clicks On The Bloc|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|page=39|date=30 August 2008}}</ref> The band members wanted to revive the importance of a new album's release in an era in which the excitement has dissipated because of extensive Internet coverage.<ref name=Scotsint/> They were inspired by [[Radiohead]]'s marketing of ''[[In Rainbows]]'' in 2007, but did not consider a "free" sale option.<ref name=RSint>{{cite web |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/08/20/bloc-partys-kele-okereke-on-intimacy-the-surprise-breakup-album-10-people-knew-about/ |title=Bloc Party's Kele Okereke on the New Album "10 People Knew About" |author=Phull, Hardeep |work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=20 August 2008|accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref> Little press was undertaken in the UK to promote the record because of Okereke's reluctance to discuss personal aspects of his life.<ref name=dummy/> 

[[File:Blocpartyreading2008B.jpg|thumb|left|200px|alt=Two guitarists, a drummer, and a bassist are performing on a smoky stage lit by white stage lights. The stage background is a black tarpaulin emblazoned with "BLOC PARTY." and a large black-and-white cityscape below it. Most of the crowd have their hands up in the foreground, which also includes a waving flag.|Bloc Party during a performance of songs from ''Intimacy'' at the 2008 Reading Festival days after the album's online release]]

''Intimacy'' was made available for download on Bloc Party's website on 21&nbsp;August 2008.<ref name=Scotsint>{{cite web|url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/sos-review/Surprise-party--Bloc-Party.4487970.jp |title=Surprise party <U+2013> Bloc Party interview|author=McLean, Craig |work=[[Scotland on Sunday]]|date=14 September 2008 |accessdate=16 May 2009 }}</ref>  Ten [[MP3]] tracks were sold with a plain black [[JPEG]] cover for <U+00A3>5, and a <U+00A3>10 option for the online songs and the future expanded CD was also available.<ref name=billb/> The album title was picked as a "double bluff" with regard to people's expectations; Okereke has explained, "You'd think of wet [[ballad]]eering. You don't think it's gonna be ugly or harsh. But that's what relationships are really like. It's not just about good times."<ref name=Scotsint/> The release was called "rushed" by publications such as ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref name=indie/><ref name=billb/> Tong disagreed with the label and stated that Bloc Party wanted to make a statement that was surprising to anyone interested in their work.<ref name=canint>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/topics/entertainment/music/story.html?id=93cccdcb-f6cb-4852-9f17-7ce2d6ad7894 |title=Bloc Party ditch the 'beaten path' |publisher=[[Canwest]] |date=9 September 2008|accessdate=16 May 2009}}</ref> 

The band showcased tracks from ''Intimacy'' at [[Reading Festival]] at the end of August 2008 and embarked on a North American tour during September.<ref name=billb/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/bloc-party/39210|title=Bloc Party bring 'Intimacy' to Reading Festival|work=[[NME]]|date=23 August 2008|accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref> UK appearances on the [[MTV Two Europe|MTV2]] Gonzo Tour and the release of the second single, "Talons", preceded the physical release of the album in October,<ref name=indie/><ref name=Scotsint/> which entered the UK Albums Chart at number eight.<ref name=everyhit/> In the U.S, the record sold 24,000 copies during the first week of release and debuted at number 18 on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSTRE4A50Z320081106|title=AC/DC album leads pop chart for second week|author=Hasty, Katie|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=5 November 2008|accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref> Comprehensive sales figures have not been published because the digital download data has not been publicly reported by Bloc Party.<ref name=billb/> The chosen [[cover art]] is a stylised shot of a couple kissing, taken by [[freelance]] photographer Perry Curties.<ref name=inlay/> It was ranked 23rd on [[Gigwise]]'s list of The Best Album Covers Of 2008, in which the publication called it "intimate and rather ambiguous".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gigwise.com/photos/48261/8/The-Best-Album-Covers-Of-2008|title=The Best Album Covers Of 2008! |author=Gigwise staff|publisher=[[Gigwise]]|date=16 December 2008|accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref>

== Content ==

=== Lyrics ===
The lyrics of ''Intimacy'' were inspired by a relationship breakup Okereke went through at the end of 2007. The lyricist told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', "I wouldn't want anyone to think it's the clich<U+00E9>d break-up record but I haven't written about true, personal experiences all that much in the past."<ref name=RSint/> The move to more intimate subject matter was "semi-conscious" because the band members did not want to focus on socio-political issues as they had in their previous works.<ref name=canint/> Three tracks allude to [[Greek mythology]]: "Ares" draws its name from the [[Ares|god of war]], "Trojan Horse" is named after the [[Trojan Horse|Trojan War military ruse]], and "Zephyrus" draws its name from the [[Zephyrus|god of the west wind]].<ref name=inlay/> The narrative in the songs occurs between two people and focuses on the relations between lovers, friends, and enemies; Okereke indicated that "it's about moments of shared vulnerability".<ref name=dummy/> "Better Than Heaven" references the [[Garden of Eden]] and [[1 Corinthians 15|Corinthians (15:22)]],<ref name=inlay/> because the lyricist wanted to explore the themes of sex and death, especially in a biblical context.<ref name=dummy/>

{{Listen
 |filename     = Bloc Party - Ion Square.ogg
 |title        = "Ion Square"
 |description  = The chorus of "Ion Square" borrows a line from E. E. Cummings and is Okereke's favourite track on the record.<ref name=inlay/><ref name=RSint/> The song contains studio effects such as [[overdubbing]].<ref name=sheetmusic/>
}}

"Biko" means "Dear" in [[Igbo language|Igbo]]<U+2014>a language spoken in Nigeria, the homeland of Okereke's parents<U+2014>and is used "when you're beseeching someone to do something". Okereke denied that it is about the murdered South African anti-[[apartheid]] protester [[Steve Biko]].  The lyrics of "One Month Off" reference feelings of anger and are about being in love with someone younger and unfaithful, while "Zephyrus" concerns an apology following neglect.<ref name=Scotsint /> The lyrics in the chorus of "Ion Square", the last track on the original download release, are based on [[E. E. Cummings]]' poem "I Carry Your Heart with Me".<ref name="inlay"/> Okereke considers the song a personal favourite because it evokes the initial exciting stages of a new relationship when everything is going right.<ref name=RSint />

=== Composition ===
Okereke has discussed a natural progression in Bloc Party's compositional style to a more explorative, electronic direction.<ref name=nb>{{cite web |url=http://herenb.canadaeast.com/music/article/418500|title=Talking Bloc during Harvest Jazz|author=O'Kane, Josh |work=[Here] New Brunswick|date=18 September 2008|accessdate=17 July 2009}}</ref> For the opening track on ''Intimacy'', "Ares", the frontman was inspired to [[rap]] his lyrics after listening to the [[old school hip hop]] of [[Afrika Bambataa]].<ref name=Fender/> According to Heather Phares of [[Allmusic]], the song includes siren-like guitar chords and loud, complex drumming in the vein of [[dance music|dance]] acts [[The Prodigy]] and [[The Chemical Brothers]].<ref name=AMG>{{cite web |url=http://allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:hzfyxzqkld6e |title= Intimacy: Bloc Party |author=Phares, Heather |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=18 May 2009}}</ref> "Mercury" continues the complex drumming theme by incorporating layered percussion and contains a vocally manipulated chorus.<ref name=sheetmusic /> The track is an attempt at [[drum and bass]] and features [[brass (instrument)|brass]] [[consonance and dissonance|dissonance]],<ref name=Fender/><ref name=sheetmusic /> effects Okereke has called "harsh, glacial, layered and energetic".<ref name=billb/> "Zephyrus" begins with a solitary vocal line accompanied only by a drum machine pattern,<ref name=sheetmusic/> while the [[Exmoor Singers]] provide [[background vocals]] in the rest of the composition.<ref name=inlay/> "Signs" is the only song that does not include guitars;<ref name=sheetmusic/> instead, it is made up of a [[synthesiser]] [[pulse (music)|pulse]] and [[multitrack recording|multitracked]] [[sample (music)|samples]] of [[glockenspiel]] and [[mbira]] resembling the work of [[minimalist music|minimalist]] composer [[Steve Reich]].<ref name=Fender/>

Okereke has conceded that ''Intimacy'' covers Bloc Party's typical indie rock elements,<ref name=Age/> but noted that the guitars have an artificial and manipulated sound, "almost like all the humanity has been bleached out".<ref name=dummy/> "Halo" has a fast [[tempo]] coupled with a guitar melody that uses only four [[chord (music)|chords]], while "Trojan Horse" features [[syncopation|syncopated]] guitars and distortion.<ref name="sheetmusic">Commercial sheet music for ''Intimacy''. [[Wichita Recordings]] Music Publishing. October 2008. Distributed by [[International Music Publications]].</ref> "Talons" also incorporates distortion from both lead and rhythm guitars,<ref name=sheetmusic /> while the final single "One Month Off" consists of tribal rhythms and [[sixteenth note]] guitar [[riff]]s.<ref name=txt/><ref name=sheetmusic /> "Biko" has a slower tempo and includes guitar [[arpeggio|arpeggi]] throughout, while "Ion Square" incorporates guitar overdubbing and the use of [[hi-hat]] patterns throughout.<ref name=sheetmusic /> According to Nick Southall of [[Drowned in Sound]], "Better Than Heaven" encapsulates what Bloc Party had been trying to achieve in their previous works, "namely aligning all their different directional desires: to swoon, to rock, and to experiment all at once".<ref name=DIS/> The track features broken beats and layered vocals.<ref name=sheetmusic/>

== Critical reception ==
{{quote box|quote=They are so solid and so confident that it seems inevitable that they will get many chances to slowly drift into more daring lands. But without more risk, they may be destined to make albums like ''Intimacy'' <U+2013> accomplished and intriguing, but not life changing, not classic.<ref name="UTR">{{Cite news |title=Year End Review 2008|author=''Under the Radar'' staff|work=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]|format=pull-out section|date=Fall 2008}}</ref>|source=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|''Under the Radar'']]'s year-end music review for 2008, on Bloc Party and the transition of the band's sound|width=20% |align=right }}

Media response to ''Intimacy'' was generally favourable; aggregating website [[Metacritic]] reported a [[standard score|normalised]] rating of 69% based on 27&nbsp;critical reviews.<ref name=metacritic>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/blocparty/intimacy?q=intimacy%20bloc|title=Intimacy by Bloc Party|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref> Steven Robertshaw of ''[[Alternative Press]]'' described the album as arguably Bloc Party's finest [[Bloc Party discography|career moment]] and noted that it offers "sweat and circuitry, savagery and submission, and a captivating energy that's severely lacking in many music scenes on the planet".<ref name=APint/> Kyle Anderson of ''Rolling Stone'' claimed that by "replacing Bloc Party's distant cool with vivid honesty, Okereke makes ''Intimacy'' a confident new peak for his band",<ref name=stone>{{cite web |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/22853075/review/22868926/intimacy|title=Bloc Party: Intimacy|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|author=Anderson, Kyle|date=18 September 2008|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref> while [[PopMatters]]' Ross Langager explained that the record "might not actually be all that intimate, but it is a thing of rough, recycled beauty".<ref name=popmatters>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/62570/bloc-party-intimacy/|title=Bloc Party: Intimacy|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|author=Langager, Ross|date=29 August 2008|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref> Adam Mazmanian of ''[[The Washington Times]]'' commented that the album's final mix showed that producers Epworth and Lee preserved the essence of Bloc Party's signature sound<U+2014>"[[minor key]] rock thrumming with rhythmic intensity"<U+2014>while taking the band in new musical directions.<ref name=WT>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2008/aug/26/intimacy-has-the-right-touch/|title=Listening Station: 'Intimacy' has the right touch|author=Mazmanian, Adam |work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=26 August 2008 |accessdate=20 July 2009}}</ref> Dave Simpson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' concluded that it would please old and new fans alike by being "brave, individual and heartfelt".<ref name=guardian>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2008/aug/29/blocparty.popandrock|title=Pop review: Bloc Party, Intimacy|author=Simpson, Dave|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 August 2008|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref>

[[Pitchfork Media]]'s Ian Cohen was less receptive and asserted that the record seems like a document of a band disconnected from its musical strengths.<ref name=pitchfork>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12130-intimacy/|title=Bloc Party: Intimacy|author=Cohen, Ian|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|date=26 August 2008|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref> Kyle Ryan of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' felt that Bloc Party should have spent more recording time on making the album.<ref name=onion/> Allmusic's Heather Phares suggested that ''Intimacy'' feels rushed and predictable at times,<ref name=AMG>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:hzfyxzqkld6e~T1|title=Intimacy: Bloc Party|author=Phares, Heather|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref> while John Robinson of ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' commented that "there's an air of slightly hedged bets".<ref name=uncut/> Drowned in Sound's Nick Southall claimed that the record is not quite the radical statement the band set out to achieve, but gave it a rating of seven out of ten, concluding that it is "definitely a little bit of invigorating redemption at a time when doubts were beginning to cloud what was, initially, a flawless reputation".<ref name=DIS>{{cite web |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/13650/reviews/3899494|title=Bloc Party: Intimacy|author=Southall, Nick|publisher=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=25 August 2008|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref> ''Intimacy'' figured in several publications' end-of-year best album lists for 2008<U+2014>notably, at number&nbsp;14 by Gigwise,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gigwise.com/article.php?id=48128&image=37#gallery|title=Gigwise's Top 50 Albums Of 2008!|author=Gigwise staff|publisher=Gigwise|date=10 December 2008|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref> at number&nbsp;36 by Drowned in Sound,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4135939-drowned-in-sounds-50-albums-of-2008|title=Drowned in Sound's 50 albums of 2008|author=Adams, Sean|publisher=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=11 December 2008|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref> and at number&nbsp;49 by ''[[NME]]''.<ref name>{{Cite news |title=Best Albums Of 2008|author=''NME'' staff|work=[[NME]]|page=18|date=13 December 2008}}</ref>

